The following is an example of hierarchical structure of  instances, the 
hierarchical relationships being established with instances of Product_class_relationship with relation_type 'hierarchy':


a high level  instance ( = enterprise) may be used to define all the  and  instances for all  instances of an enterprise 
with several brands and companies;

a second level  instance ( = designer) may be used to group all products that are based on the same concept (for example the same designer); these products may belong to different brands;

a third level  instance ( = product family) may be used to group all products that have a common base and a fixed set of characteristics (specification categories);

a fourth level  instance ( = product type) may represent products that are offered to the market; this level of  may be defined by the marketing department. A set of specifications sufficient to produce the product is associated with this level of . Within this association, a distinction is made between standard characteristics (for example 'number of doors') and options that have to be chosen (for example, 'colour') or that may be chosen by the customer 
(for example, 'additional features').
